title: For Sale/Trade:  Beautiful 50 Year Old Winchester
postcontent:
Up for sale or trade is a beautiful, and probably unfired Winchester Model 94 lever action rifle in .30-30 caliber. Based on the serial number, the rifle is 50 years old, but looks brand new. I took it in trade to get a handgun in the deal that I wanted, but since I am disabled, I will probably never use it. It would be a real shame for this piece of American history to just sit in my safe.
If you are familiar with Winchester 94's, you know they can be used for everything from home defense to hog or deer hunting, but you also know that today's Winchester 94's are made in Japan, have a weird cross-bolt safety that nobody likes, and cost $975 new. Winchester has not made a 94 in the USA since 2006, but I have one for you right here if you want to own a true classic.
Feel free to call or text me at REDACTED
The rifle does not have a box, but it does come with two brand new boxes of Federal ammunition, and a butt mounted cartridge holder. The rifle is spotless and has been really well kept. The owner told me he bought it new in 1965 and could not remember ever firing it. It certainly looks that way. I'm looking to turn it into cash, but will consider trades or partial trades for quality handguns. I will entertain reasonable offers.
Please, let's not waste each other's time with ridiculously low offers. I have many more detailed pictures if you would like to see them.

title: For Sale:  Pre-War Colt Sport Model Woodsman 4 1/2" Inch Barrel in Nice Wood Case
postcontent: Designed by John Browning and put into production by Colt in 1915, the Colt Woodsman has been one of the most popular .22 automatic pistols in the world since it's inception.  This Woodsman, was made in 1936 and remains in near-mint condition.  The original factory blue finish rates 98%, and the bore and factory checkered wooden grips are mint.  The only finish wear on the gun is just the very slightest thinning on the high edge of the slide, and the very bottom right edge of the rear grip strap.  Everything works on this pistol just the way it did when it left the Colt factory.  It is obvious that this pistol has seen very little use and handling in it's life.  This Woodsman comes with a very nicely fitted period wooden case with a minty factory extra magazine, a period oiler, a old glass bottle of gun oil, and an aluminum cleaning rod.  Everything fits nice and snug in the custom box, and the blue felt lining is nearly perfect as well.  It is apparent that this case was specifically built for this pistol and these extra items rather than altered to fit them.  This Sport Model Colt Woodsman is as nice a pre-war Woodsman as we have had in recent history in this configuration, and would be nearly impossible to upgrade.

title: For Sale/Trade:  *New* *Unfired*
postcontent: just a friendly reminder: Unless you have a FFL you cannot sell a gun as "new." If a gun has been purchased by any other person it cannot be advertised for sale as new. You can list it as "unfired" and be perfectly legal. We need to watch our language before our helpful government makes more attempts to prevent the legal re-sale of a firearm. Let's be better at how we list things and not give the government an opportunity to "correct" us!Thanks!

I would encourage you to do some research on these lowers if you have not heard of them. In many ways they are STRONGER than aluminum while being 2-3 ounces lighter. Unlike traditional polymer lowers, these have marine brass fittings for the buffer tube as well as the grip threads which provided metal contact points for all threaded parts. Go to Youtube and watch some videos on these lowers...you will be impressed.Ok, here are the components that went into them. As you can see this is not low end parts.1.) 7075 Mil Spec Buffer Tube...many use 6061 Aluminum which is much softer.2.) Magpul MOE Stock3.) Magpul MIAD Grip or Stock A2 Trigger4.) Nickle Teflon Hammer & Trigger5.) JP Trigger Springs6.) Anderson Lower Vitals minue fire control groupHave you ever bought a lower and the trigger felt like crap? If you want a high end trigger many of them can cost $200 or more. These triggers are awesome. The triggers contact surfaces are polished, they are then coated in nickle teflon, finally they are lightly polished after coating them. When you combine this trigger with JP reduced power springs you end up with a trigger that has a pull weight around 5 lbs, and more importantly it is EXTREMELY smooth. 1.)
